{{Infobox organization | name = Meher Spiritual Center | logo = Boat House Meher Center.jpg | logo_size = 275px | motto = ''A place of pilgrimage for all time'' | type = [[Nonprofit organization]] | founded = 1944 | location = [[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina]] | key_people = | fields = | services = | num_members = | homepage = [http://www.mehercenter.org mehercenter.org] }} The '''Meher Spiritual Center''' is a {{convert|500|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[Retreat (spiritual)|spiritual retreat]] along the Atlantic Ocean between [[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina|Myrtle Beach]] and [[North Myrtle Beach, South Carolina]] and adjacent to [[Briarcliffe Acres, South Carolina|Briarcliffe Acres]]. The Center was established by Elizabeth Chapin Patterson and [[Norina Matchabelli|Princess Norina Matchabelli]] in the early 1940s under the guidance of Indian spiritual master [[Meher Baba]] as ''A place of pilgrimage for all time''.<ref>Purdom, Charles, ''The God-Man: The Life, Journeys & Work of Meher Baba with an Interpretation of His Silence & Spiritual Teaching'', George Allen & Unwin, London, 1964, p. 201</ref> Its stated purpose is to exist as a "retreat for rest, meditation, and renewal of the spiritual life.”<ref>[http://www.mehercenter.org/ Mehercenter.org]</ref>
The Meher Spiritual Center is also designated as a South Carolina [[Wildlife refuge|wildlife sanctuary]], with more than 200 species of plants, 100 species of birds and 44 species of animals.<ref>[http://www.scwf.org/index.php/education-programs/habitats/community/50-briarcliffe South Carolina Wildlife Federation (retrieved 8-12-2014)]</ref> The Center has two lakes, many nature trails, and a mile of Atlantic shoreline. The Center has a house built for Meher Baba which is named "Meher Abode" but usually referred to as "Baba's House." Meher Baba stayed there during his three visits to America in the 1950s. Meher Baba inaugurated the Meher Center in 1952 and also visited in 1956 and 1958.<ref name="Meher Center History">[http://www.mehercenter.org/pastandpresent/history.html Meher Center History]</ref>
== History == Meher Baba requested that the land for his center in America meet certain criteria. They were: the place must have equitable climate, virgin soil, ample water, soil that could be made self-sustaining to a large number of people, and the property should be given from the heart.<ref>Kalchuri, Bhau, ''Meher Prabu, Lord Meher'', Manifestation, 1986, p. 2951</ref> Elizabeth Patterson and Norina Matchabelli originally sought land in other parts of the United States including California. But no land met all the requirements. Eventually Elizabeth Patterson's father, [[Simeon B. Chapin]], who was one of the original developers of Myrtle Beach, gave her the land as a gift. He felt that it was not suitable for his resort plans since its lakes obstructed access to the beach.<ref name="Meher Center History"/>
